flowRoot.flowPara: The Role of Communication Mimicry in the
Development of Rapport and
Interpersonal Influence
Tom Carrick
Supervisors: Awais Rashid, Paul J. Taylor, Adam Joinson
Background
When interacting with others, humans show a tendency to mimic one anothers behavior, including speech, physical actions and written text.

This mimicry is useful for humans as it is used as a basis for learning, and has been shown to improve performance in group tasks. Measures of mimicry can also be an indicator of successful relationships, and importantly, an indicator of deception.
When interacting with others, humans show a tendency to mimic one anothers behaviour, including speech, physical actions and written text.
People who mimic each other's language have more successful outcomes in joint tasks. Mimicry is also a measure of social cohesion and "liking".
Detection of mimicry can be a valuable indicator in conversations between two people as well as group dynamics in collaborative settings.

As well as looking to improve the performance of the detection of mimicry, this project will look at how mimicry can be used both offensively to aid in attacks against systems, and how it can be used defensively to protect against security threats.

Current work

My current work focuses on the Interactive Alignment Model (IAM) [1], shown above, which is the prevailing model of mimicry according to cognitive science. Mimicry is said to flow between the different levels of the model, the situation model, and the semantic, syntactic and lexical representation layers. The situation model encodes space, time, causality, intentionality, and reference to individuals under discussion, while the lower layers represent the utterance at different levels. It is stated that mimicry on one level leads to increased mimicry in ajoining layers.

For each layer we use a computational technique (discussed top-right) to capture mimicry at that particular layer. These results can then be compared with baseline results taken from expert human classifiers' scoring at each layer.
In particular, I attempt to answer the following questions:
1. Do current mimicry detection measures work in the context
of the IAM?
2. How well do they compare to expert human classifiers?
3. How can we get the best results from these techniques?
Future work

As part of my project I will build a chat bot that can mimic the language of its human conversation partner to varying degrees in an attempt to find the "sweet spot" for mimicry, where positive interpersonal outcomes are more likely to occur.
Potential implications
The potential implications of my work are:
Increased accuracy of current mimicry detection
techniques
Assess the level of rapport between interaction partners
Establish if and where the "sweet spot" of mimicry exists
Increase efficacy of detecting insider threats
Determine if mimicry can be exploited for social
engineering or other attacks
Results so far
To date I have found that:
Human classifiers generally agree with each other on
mimicry at all levels, but particularly at the lexical level
All computational techniques correlated with the
classifiers' opinions in their respective layers
As predicted by the IAM, increased mimicry in one
layer correlates with increased mimicry in other layers.
Both humans and the computation techniques used
were less useful for finding mimicry at the semantic
layer than at the other layers.
LSM appears to work at the syntactic layer, and in my
tests, better than the actual syntactic technique used
Computational techniques
Local Linguistic Alignment (LLA) works at the lexical
level by determining the probability of each word from
the first text to appear at a specific point in the second.
LLA can also be used at the syntactic level by
substituting words with pieces of syntax.
Word vectors compare semantic similarity by grouping
similar words together in vector space.
Language Style Matching (LSM) uses function words to
compare people's linguistic style.
